| image=USCapitol1827A.gif imagedate= 1827
}} The 'Sixteenth United States Congress' was a meeting of the legislative
branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States
Senate and the United States House of Representatives. It met in Washington,
D.C. from March 4, 1819 to March 4, 1821, during the third and fourth years of
James Monroe's presidency. The apportionment of seats in the House of
Representatives was based on the Third Census of the United States in 1810. Both
chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
